New image-based stuff

Outline

So the gist of the image-based workflow is:

  • getimg(): Load up an image or images. Similar in structure to getspec. So if a full path to an image is passed, it just grabs that image, but if a directory is specified it grabs everything in there as long as it’s jpeg, png, or bmp. With subdirectory options etc too of course. So all the downstream functions are built to handle either single images (a 3d RGB array), or multiple images (a list of 3d RGB arrays) gracefully, without the user having to lapply everything. That’s why if you look at the internals of the downstream functions they’re structured a bit unusually, since the top-level (user-called) bit basically just handles some defaults and light processing, before passing everything through, via pbmclapply or lapply, to an internal function that does the grunt work. And images are of class rimg for downstream stuff.
  • calibrate(): (optional). Currently lets you click on points in an image or images to manually set a scale, which is stored as an attribute for later use. If the images are standardised this can be ignored and a single scale can be set later on I could also see this being expanded to accommodate more features, like automatic image alignment, in the future, but I think keep it lightweight for now.
  • classify(): This uses k-means clustering to assign every pixel to a discrete ‘colour class’, which is necessary for various pattern analyses that exist atm. There are options to manually click on images to assign cluster centers and/or specify a reference image so that clusters are consistently assigned between homologous pattern elements between individuals. There’s always that question of ‘what is a distinct patch’ inherent in these methods of course, but that’s actually one of the cool areas where having this woven into pavo makes a difference. Since if you have that spectral data from your sample too you can run your RN bootstraps and actually estimate k with some sensory significance, all in one place. That’d be worth illustrating in the write-up/vignette but I can’t be arsed atm…
  • adjacent() This runs John’s adjacency analysis, including his ‘edge-salience’ extension which I don’t think is quite out yet. Should be in MEE soon. The gist being that you burn through and grab all pair-wise row and column transitions between colour-classes (adjacency matrix) then you can derive a boatload of summary variables on pattern structure, like aspect ratio, element sizes, pattern complexity and density, colour diversity, transition diversity, edge salience (if you also feed in colour distances between colour categories), animal/background transition ratios etc. You can also explicitly exclude the ‘background’, or analyse it separately. The biological meaning of some of this stuff isn’t super clear, it’s more of a hypothesis-generation affair at times, but it at least gives the user a bunch of material to work with for little investment (some basic photos in addition to the specs, or even if you don’t have specs you can get most of this stuff just from photos). Then you can test all ideas about whole patterns, rather than coloru alone. E.g. Colour diversity and complexity should be similar for cryptic species and their backgrounds, ‘memorable’ signals should have low diversity and complexity, disruptively coloured things should exhibit greater edge-salience to break-up their outline etc.
  • plot(): Can be fed raw or colour-classified images for easy plotting. In the case of colour-classified images it’ll colour the image with the mean RGB values from each cluster, which makes it easier to see if it’s grouped things as you’d expect. If it’s fed a list of images it’ll just scroll the user through them all with a keyboard-push.
  • summary.rimg(): Spits out some summary attribute data, or plots the mean colour-values from colour classified images.

So in a broader sense I see the workflow as roughly being: Get -> Calibrate -> Classify -> Analyse (adjacency). Since it’s structured in a fairly modular way there’s plenty of scope to expand stuff in the future as need be. e.g. more calibration options, different classification tools, or further analyses. But as it stands I think it offers a cool level of functionality.

Crappy examples

Load up.

devtools::install_github('rmaia/pavo@img')
library(pavo)

Load an image of a butterfly, and a series of images of simulated (based on real species) model/mimic aposematic snakes

# One image
papilio <- getimg(system.file("testdata/images/papilio.png", package = 'pavo'))

# Many images
snakes <- getimg(system.file("testdata/images/snakes", package = 'pavo'))
## 11 files found; importing images.

Some raw plots.

plot(papilio)

# Just plot a couple of snakes since it'll otherwise it'll try to click you through. Maybe this should be an option actually..
par(mfrow = c(3,1))
plot(snakes[[1]])
plot(snakes[[4]])
plot(snakes[[8]])

Cool. I won’t worry about calibrating thtem since that’s interactive.

Now classify stuff.

set.seed(4)

papilio_class <- classify(papilio, n_cols = 4)

snakes_class <- classify(snakes, n_cols = 3)

And plot again. Here’s a side-by-side example.

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(papilio, main = 'raw')
plot(papilio_class, main = 'classified')

The classified one just looks a bit weirdly smooth. It shows the clustering works well though.

You can also get a quick summary of the colours being used with summary(plot = TRUE).

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(papilio_class, main = 'classified')
summary(papilio_class, plot = TRUE)

Now churn it through the adjacency analysis. As mentioned, you basically grid-sample the image (or just us all pixels):

plot(papilio_class, main = 'classified', x_pts = 20)

then tally up all row-wise and column-wise transitions, and crunch them into various summary variables about the spatial structure of the pattern.

The actual analysis:

Tons of output there, and the user doesn’t need to get all of it tbh, some of it is just there while I’m still checking it. Some NA’s in there because not all transitions are present in different species etc.

Fun stuff anyway, and will play nicely with the spectral side of things for a much richer set of information. Sorry for the lame examples here — hopefully makes the point though.
